
## React/TypeScript Development Conventions

### Code Quality Stack
Run `yarn lint:all` (or equivalent) — executes in order:
1. `tsc --noEmit` — type errors
2. `oxlint --deny-warnings` or `biome check` — fast lint
3. `eslint .` — semantic rules, React hooks
4. `biome format .` or `prettier --check .` — formatting

### Biome Lint Checklist
Before committing JS/TS changes, verify no:
- Duplicate className attributes (most common)
- noAssignInExpressions violations
- noNonNullAssertion warnings
- React hooks dependency violations
- Unused imports
- SVG accessibility warnings (role, aria-label)
Run `npx @biomejs/biome check <file>` on changed files before staging.

### Component Testing Patterns
```typescript
import { render, screen, fireEvent } from '@testing-library/react'
import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest'

describe('MyComponent', () => {
  it('renders correctly', () => {
    render(<MyComponent title="Test" />)
    expect(screen.getByText('Test')).toBeInTheDocument()
  })

  it('handles user interaction', async () => {
    const onSubmit = vi.fn()
    render(<MyComponent onSubmit={onSubmit} />)
    fireEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i }))
    expect(onSubmit).toHaveBeenCalledOnce()
  })
})
```

### React/TS Logging Conventions
```typescript
// Error boundaries MUST log
console.error('[ComponentName] Render error:', error, errorInfo)
// API calls MUST log failures
console.warn('[API] Failed to fetch:', endpoint, response.status)
// State transitions in complex components
console.info('[ComponentName] State change:', { from, to, trigger })
```

